<br>
    1.  They lack the only two things neccessary to   <br>
authenticate a photo- the picture and the negative.<br>
<br>
    2.  More &quot;orbs&quot; are captured with digital cameras because in low-light conditions, if the CCD cannot differentiate between the background and the focus object, it sometimes leaves the spot blank, resulting in a supposed &quot;orb&quot;.<br>
<br>
     There may be other reasons, but those are mine (as you can see, I'm kind of biased).  This is not to say that digital cameras are not a good back-up tool, but it's why I feel they should not be used alone.<br>
<br>
     There are also infrared cameras, which take pictures of the infrared (the lightwaves just under the range of human sight in the light spectrum) signatures in a photo.  These are very tricky, though, as the infrared film is very sensitive and ruins easily if not properly handled.  Cheap, disposable cameras work just as well as the more expensive models, but again there are many differant opinions on that.  I do know that different film speeds affect pictures differently, so you have to find one that gives you results you are comfortable with.<br>
<br>
    Ghost hunters also use video cameras for obvious reasons, but while I'm not sure about the same effect happening with the digital ones, it seems a safe bet that it will, since they both use CCD's (charge-coupled devices, a type of lens).<br>
<br>
    EMF meters are a good device used to measure the electromagnetic field in an area.  EMF seems to increase when spirit activity is present, but when using these meters you -must- be able to rule out natural and man-made fields before you can say &quot;Okay, yeah that was a ghost.&quot;  A very cheap and common emf detector is a compass.  The needle will point to the direction of the field if it comes into contact with one.  The only downfall to emf meters is that they all have the same range: 0 feet.  No matter how sensitive they are, they have to be in direct contact with a field to sense it.  There currently is no way to remotely measure a magnetic field.  The curious thing about magnetic fields is that they are the only event that cannot be directly measured; we can only measure their effects.<br>
<br>
    Thermometers are used because of the phenomenon known as &quot;cold spots&quot;.  The (theoretically) scientific explaination of a cold spot is that in order to manifest themselves, ghosts need energy, and they get that energy from the heat in the air around them.  You could liken it to a geothermal electrical plant, only with an instantaneous conversion instead of the steam turbines.  Infrared thermometers use the infrared signature of the object they are pointed at to calculate the temperature in about 1/500 of a second.  <br>
       <br>
     There are various other devices such as Geiger counters, ion counters, and the like to detect and measure the radioactive and ionic signatures that have been found to increase with spirit activity, but they are very, very expensive.   Some people like to use dowsing rods, which are two thin rods of a pure metal bent into an &quot;L&quot; shape and held loosely in the hands.  When they make contact with a ghost, they are said to cross.  This seems to be a knd of subjective operation to me, but as with all other devices, none should be used alone to make a qualifying decision as to whether or not a location is haunted.  <br>
<br>
     The most important thing to remember is that you have to rule out natural and man-made causes before you can make your final decision about a haunting.  How embarrassing would it be if you had the data, didn't analyze it properly, and made the announcement to your peers &quot;Yes, this place is haunted!&quot; and later it came out that it was a hoax?  Not only that, but when you do this, you discredit other, more thorough ghost hunters in a field that is already rife with derision from the more &quot;proper&quot; scientific fields.  It is important, too, to retain an open mind while applying cold, hard logic.  You must approach an investigation in a manner that suggests you are trying to prove a location is -not- haunted.<br>
<br>
     I apologize for such a long speech, but I hope you found it helpful.  I am by no means an expert on these things, so before you take my word as gold, my advice would be to do your own research and come to your own conclusions.  Thank you for your patience.<br>
<br>
